---
title: Peppercorn Steak with Baby Potatoes & Creamed Spinach
description: We all love a creamy peppercorn sauce. Pour it over juicy sliced steak and roast potatoes and you’ll have the ultimate dish for Valentine’s Day.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/54c906c06ced6e7c1d8b4568.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/54c906c06ced6e7c1d8b4568.pdf
servings: 2
course: main course
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/peppercorn-steak-54c906c06ced6e7c1d8b4568
author: HelloFresh
cuisine: North America
nutrition:
  calories: 570 kcal
  fat: 27 g
  carbohydrates: 42 g
  protein: 45 g
  fiber: 7 g
time required: 30 minutes
---

Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Take the @sirloin steak{1} out of the fridge to bring to room temperature. Toss the @baby red potatoes{10%ounce} with @olive oil{1%tablespoon} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} and spread them out on a #baking sheet{}. Roast for ~{25-30%minutes}, until golden brown and easily pierced with a knife.

> If the potatoes are too big, cut them into quarters!

Meanwhile, finely mince the @shallot{1}.

Heat @butter{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add the @spinach{8%ounce} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, tossing, until wilted, about ~{5%minutes}. Add a splash of water and half the @sour cream{2%tablespoon}. Stir to combine and season with salt and pepper. Set aside off the heat and cover to keep warm.

Season the steak with salt and pepper. Heat @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a pan over medium heat. Sear the steak for ~{4-6%minutes} per side (depending on thickness), until golden brown. Set aside to rest.

In the same pan you cooked the steak in, add the shallots and cook for ~{1-2%minutes}. Add the @veggie stock concentrate{1}, @water{1/2%cup}, @cracked black pepper{1/4-1/2%teaspoon} and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Cook over medium heat until reduced until slightly thickened. Add the remaining @sour cream{2%tablespoon} and stir to combine. Season with salt and pepper. Simmer until slightly thickened.

> Cracking black pepper yourself imparts so much more flavor and it's super easy! Place some whole peppercorns in a plastic bag and smash with the bottom of a pot, a rolling pin, or a mallet.

Thinly slice the steak against the grain. Spoon the peppercorn sauce over the steak and serve with creamed spinach and roasted potatoes to the side.